1. Define the domain and range for the function \( \log(x+1) \).
2. Plot the function \( \log(x+1) \) for \( x \geq 0 \).
3. Extend the function to include the part where \( x < 0 \) by setting it to \( 0 \).

Here's the TikZ code to achieve this:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
    % Draw the axes
    \draw[->] (-2,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$x$};
    \draw[->] (0,-1) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};

    % Draw the log(x+1) function for x >= 0
    \draw[blue, thick] plot[domain=0:3,samples=100] (\x, {ln(\x + 1)});

    % Draw the line y = 0 for x < 0
    \draw[red, dashed] plot[domain=-2:0,samples=100] (\x, {0});

    % Label the regions
    \node at (1,1) [anchor=south west] {Region I: \( x \geq 0 \)};
    \node at (-1,-0.5) [anchor=north east] {Region II: \( x < 0 \)};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
